1
00:00:00,689 --> 00:00:01,879
<i>Previously on Gotham...</i>

2
00:00:01,942 --> 00:00:03,304
Welcome to Wayne Enterprises.

3
00:00:03,319 --> 00:00:04,919
I have some questions
regarding Wayne Enterprises'

4
00:00:04,954 --> 00:00:06,320
business affairs.

5
00:00:08,991 --> 00:00:10,057
Where's Jim?

6
00:00:13,463 --> 00:00:15,596
Don Falcone thinks you
don't know how to run a club.

7
00:00:15,631 --> 00:00:17,281
- (whistles)
- Hi.

8
00:00:17,319 --> 00:00:18,719
He'll help you out.

9
00:00:18,754 --> 00:00:19,853
Those people out there

10
00:00:19,888 --> 00:00:22,589
<i>are using us as spare parts.</i>

11
00:00:22,624 --> 00:00:24,825
<i>Unless we do something about it.</i>

12
00:00:24,860 --> 00:00:26,293
Alfred, can you teach me how to fight?

13
00:00:26,328 --> 00:00:27,494
Yes, I can.

14
00:00:27,529 --> 00:00:29,329
<i>BULLOCK: Pretty handy for a valet.</i>

15
00:00:29,365 --> 00:00:30,831
<i>ALFRED: Butler, mate.</i>

16
00:00:30,866 --> 00:00:31,865
I'm a butler.

17
00:00:33,102 --> 00:00:35,102
(tires screeching)

18
00:01:01,850 --> 00:01:03,016
What the hell is that?

19
00:01:03,051 --> 00:01:04,951
- I made it. Yeah.
- You made it?

20
00:01:04,987 --> 00:01:06,887
- So what is it?
- It's a hood.

21
00:01:06,922 --> 00:01:08,889
Thought it would, uh,
you know, spice things up.

22
00:01:08,924 --> 00:01:10,357
When did we start wearing hoods?

23
00:01:10,392 --> 00:01:12,726
- We didn't.
- W-Was I supposed to get one?

24
00:01:12,761 --> 00:01:14,761
No!

25
00:01:20,335 --> 00:01:22,002
(panicked shouting, gasping)

26
00:01:23,171 --> 00:01:24,738
Ladies... And gentlemen,

27
00:01:24,773 --> 00:01:26,473
we are not here for your money!

28
00:01:26,508 --> 00:01:28,742
We're here for the bank's money!

29
00:01:28,777 --> 00:01:31,511
So just stay cool and no one will get hurt!

30
00:01:32,514 --> 00:01:34,381
Don't be brave!

31
00:01:34,416 --> 00:01:36,249
Don't be frightened!

32
00:01:36,285 --> 00:01:37,684
Just do what you're told!

33
00:01:37,719 --> 00:01:39,419
This will all be over
quicker than that time

34
00:01:39,454 --> 00:01:41,521
I hooked up with a
cheerleader on prom night!

35
00:01:41,557 --> 00:01:42,789
(man chuckles)

36
00:01:42,824 --> 00:01:44,224
What are you doing up there?!

37
00:01:44,259 --> 00:01:45,926
Getting 'em fired up.

38
00:01:45,961 --> 00:01:46,993
90 seconds.

39
00:01:47,029 --> 00:01:49,529
Nice and easy, ladies and gentlemen!

40
00:01:49,565 --> 00:01:52,432
You know, banks like this
one... Who are insured

41
00:01:52,467 --> 00:01:56,503
to death, by the way... Steal
from us every single day!

42
00:01:56,538 --> 00:01:59,673
'Bout time a few of us returned
the favor, don't you think?

43
00:01:59,708 --> 00:02:01,875
60 seconds.

44
00:02:01,910 --> 00:02:04,177
You're being great, folks! Almost done!

45
00:02:07,950 --> 00:02:09,416
40 seconds.

46
00:02:09,451 --> 00:02:11,551
(gunshots)

47
00:02:11,587 --> 00:02:13,687
(people gasping, shrieking)

48
00:02:13,722 --> 00:02:15,722
- (gun clicking)
- (chuckles)

49
00:02:15,757 --> 00:02:17,357
Nothing!

50
00:02:17,392 --> 00:02:19,960
Not a scratch! (cackling)

51
00:02:20,762 --> 00:02:22,996
Th-Thirty seconds.

52
00:02:23,031 --> 00:02:24,531
Let's get out of here!

53
00:02:27,603 --> 00:02:30,403
You've been great, ladies
and germs, but we got to go!

54
00:02:30,439 --> 00:02:32,439
(chuckles)

55
00:02:34,409 --> 00:02:36,276
Did you see that?

56
00:02:36,311 --> 00:02:39,199
- That guy missed me with, like, six shots.
- He was, old, nervous.

57
00:02:39,224 --> 00:02:41,191
No, no, no, it's the hood. I'm telling you.

58
00:02:41,226 --> 00:02:43,660
Damn it. We're cooked.

59
00:02:43,695 --> 00:02:45,729
(sirens wailing)

60
00:02:47,599 --> 00:02:50,734
Attention, citizens of Gotham!

61
00:02:50,769 --> 00:02:52,002
What the hell are you doing?!

62
00:02:52,037 --> 00:02:53,837
There you go, everybody!

63
00:02:53,872 --> 00:02:55,372
(cheering, shouting)

64
00:02:55,407 --> 00:02:58,108
Take back what's yours!

65
00:02:58,143 --> 00:03:00,911
(cheering, shouting)

66
00:03:03,215 --> 00:03:05,048
Follow me! Come on.

67
00:03:05,084 --> 00:03:07,584
(clamoring)

68
00:03:18,430 --> 00:03:20,430
(indistinct chatter, cameras clicking)

69
00:03:29,007 --> 00:03:31,208
BULLOCK: Well,

70
00:03:31,243 --> 00:03:33,577
we'll never know how much cash was lost,

71
00:03:33,612 --> 00:03:36,513
but I just saw a bum eating
oysters at Madeline's.

72
00:03:36,548 --> 00:03:39,783
Another freak in a mask. Awesome.

73
00:03:39,818 --> 00:03:43,620
Is that guard blind or wasted?

74
00:03:43,655 --> 00:03:45,789
Clyde refused to wear his glasses.

75
00:03:45,824 --> 00:03:47,591
Said they made him look old.

76
00:03:47,626 --> 00:03:50,227
Missing a man standing 20 feet
in front of you with six shots

77
00:03:50,262 --> 00:03:51,595
makes you look old.

78
00:03:51,630 --> 00:03:53,263
- Who tripped the alarm?
- I did.

79
00:03:53,298 --> 00:03:55,799
Why aren't you out there, Detective?

80
00:03:55,834 --> 00:03:59,236
This brazen audacity cannot be tolerated.

81
00:03:59,271 --> 00:04:02,005
They didn't go for the
vault... just the cash

82
00:04:02,040 --> 00:04:04,007
in the registers. And
the crew was in and out

83
00:04:04,042 --> 00:04:05,909
in under two minutes.

84
00:04:05,944 --> 00:04:07,711
The red-hooded man seemed nice.

85
00:04:07,746 --> 00:04:09,079
Nice?

86
00:04:09,114 --> 00:04:11,915
He wasn't stealing our
money... just the bank's.

87
00:04:11,950 --> 00:04:13,450
Then he gave a lot of it

88
00:04:13,485 --> 00:04:15,452
back to people in the street. Like...

89
00:04:16,421 --> 00:04:18,255
Robin Hood.

90
00:04:18,290 --> 00:04:20,924
Oh, great. This bank hires Communists.

91
00:04:20,959 --> 00:04:23,460
Robin Hood stole from the
rich and gave to the poor.

92
00:04:23,495 --> 00:04:25,795
These armed thieves only threw cash away

93
00:04:25,831 --> 00:04:27,297
to guarantee their escape.

94
00:04:27,332 --> 00:04:29,132
It's very different, ma'am.

95
00:04:29,168 --> 00:04:30,667
The thief

96
00:04:30,702 --> 00:04:33,158
in the back here, was he
always checking his watch?

97
00:04:33,208 --> 00:04:35,205
Yes. He was counting down.

98
00:04:35,240 --> 00:04:37,040
They knew what our response time was.

99
00:04:37,075 --> 00:04:38,308
They'd done their homework.

100
00:04:38,343 --> 00:04:40,277
Has the alarm been triggered
for any other reason recently?

101
00:04:40,312 --> 00:04:42,312
- No.
- Well,

102
00:04:42,347 --> 00:04:44,681
there was that time with the smoke bomb.

103
00:04:44,716 --> 00:04:45,749
Smoke bomb?

104
00:04:45,784 --> 00:04:48,218
A week or so ago, a
small flare or firework,

105
00:04:48,253 --> 00:04:49,753
or something, was set
off by the Mortgages desk.

106
00:04:49,788 --> 00:04:52,489
It tripped the alarm. We thought

107
00:04:52,524 --> 00:04:54,558
it was just a kid's prank.

108
00:04:54,593 --> 00:04:56,393
We're gonna need you to
find the surveillance footage

109
00:04:56,428 --> 00:04:57,694
from that incident.

110
00:04:58,897 --> 00:05:01,698
- (thunder crashing)
- (knocking on door)

111
00:05:02,734 --> 00:05:04,734
(knocking continues)

112
00:05:16,381 --> 00:05:18,582
Yes, sir. How can I help you?

113
00:05:22,454 --> 00:05:23,820
Reggie?

114
00:05:23,855 --> 00:05:26,356
Sorry for calling so late.

115
00:05:26,391 --> 00:05:28,458
Forgive me.

116
00:05:28,493 --> 00:05:30,860
Oh, my God, mate. How long's it been?

117
00:05:30,896 --> 00:05:33,897
20 years.

118
00:05:35,634 --> 00:05:37,934
I got picked up by the GCPD last night

119
00:05:37,970 --> 00:05:41,204
for trying to sleep
under the Westbury Bridge.

120
00:05:41,240 --> 00:05:43,473
- Here, mate.
- Cheers, mate.

121
00:05:43,508 --> 00:05:47,377
One of the officers was
a Marine, back in the day,

122
00:05:47,412 --> 00:05:49,546
so we got to talking. I told him

123
00:05:49,581 --> 00:05:52,549
I was with Her Majesty's Special
Air Service back in the day.

124
00:05:52,584 --> 00:05:54,017
So he took pity on me.

125
00:05:54,052 --> 00:05:57,921
He says, "Why don't you look
up some of your old regiment,

126
00:05:57,956 --> 00:06:00,924
you know, see if one of the
guys can... help you out."

127
00:06:00,959 --> 00:06:02,959
Well, you know...

128
00:06:04,563 --> 00:06:06,730
I'm pleased you looked me up, Reg.

129
00:06:06,765 --> 00:06:08,732
If anyone would've told me

130
00:06:08,767 --> 00:06:12,035
this is where I'd find you,
I wouldn't have believed them.

131
00:06:12,070 --> 00:06:13,220
I like it here.

132
00:06:15,407 --> 00:06:17,507
It's good for me.

133
00:06:17,542 --> 00:06:19,776
I can see that.

134
00:06:19,811 --> 00:06:22,312
I've missed you, mate.

135
00:06:22,347 --> 00:06:24,581
Missed your ugly mug.

136
00:06:26,084 --> 00:06:27,884
Cheers.

137
00:06:28,920 --> 00:06:30,517
What happened, Reggie?

138
00:06:32,924 --> 00:06:34,858
Vanessa died.

139
00:06:34,893 --> 00:06:37,594
11 years ago now.

140
00:06:37,629 --> 00:06:40,597
I just couldn't find the energy

141
00:06:40,632 --> 00:06:44,267
to get back out there after that, you know?

142
00:06:44,303 --> 00:06:47,237
A year later, I lost the house.

143
00:06:47,272 --> 00:06:49,406
Moved back to Gotham.

144
00:06:49,441 --> 00:06:51,675
I've had a few jobs.

145
00:06:51,710 --> 00:06:54,544
Nothing I'm proud of.

146
00:06:57,482 --> 00:06:59,683
It was the drink, Alfie.

147
00:07:01,586 --> 00:07:03,920
It was the drink.

148
00:07:03,955 --> 00:07:05,455
BRUCE: Alfred?

149
00:07:07,292 --> 00:07:09,159
Um, Master Bruce.

150
00:07:09,194 --> 00:07:10,927
This is, uh,

151
00:07:10,962 --> 00:07:12,729
Reginald Payne.

152
00:07:12,764 --> 00:07:14,698
We served together, sir.

153
00:07:16,935 --> 00:07:18,635
Very pleased to meet you, sir.

154
00:07:18,670 --> 00:07:20,303
You were caught in the storm?

155
00:07:20,339 --> 00:07:22,572
Reggie's had a run of
bad luck, Master Bruce.

156
00:07:22,607 --> 00:07:24,908
I-I don't wish to be a nuisance. I just...

157
00:07:24,943 --> 00:07:28,178
I hadn't seen Alfie in a very long time.

158
00:07:28,213 --> 00:07:31,781
N-No, I'm glad you found us, Mr. Payne.

159
00:07:31,817 --> 00:07:34,317
Please, feel free to
stay with us a few days.

160
00:07:35,687 --> 00:07:37,487
That's very kind of you, but...

161
00:07:37,522 --> 00:07:38,588
I insist.

162
00:07:39,991 --> 00:07:41,024
Please.

163
00:07:45,364 --> 00:07:47,330
MOONEY: Where are you taking me?

164
00:07:47,366 --> 00:07:49,532
MAN: This way, Miss Mooney.

165
00:07:49,568 --> 00:07:51,568
(moaning, shouting in distance)

166
00:08:18,730 --> 00:08:20,697
Who chose these people?

167
00:08:20,732 --> 00:08:22,732
Where'd you get them from?

168
00:08:34,346 --> 00:08:35,645
(door shuts)

169
00:08:35,680 --> 00:08:38,248
(lock clicks)

170
00:08:39,384 --> 00:08:41,885
Sit, please.

171
00:08:46,258 --> 00:08:48,258
Sit.

172
00:08:56,835 --> 00:08:59,636
There you are, Mr. Red Hood.

173
00:08:59,671 --> 00:09:01,571
Armed robbery perps dating back ten years.

174
00:09:01,606 --> 00:09:03,907
I took out the dead ones
and the ones in prison.

175
00:09:03,942 --> 00:09:05,241
A who's who of scumbags.

176
00:09:05,277 --> 00:09:07,811
They were casing the place a
week before they took it down.

177
00:09:07,846 --> 00:09:10,380
Set off the alarm then timed the response.

178
00:09:10,415 --> 00:09:12,916
He looks pretty young.
He might not be in here.

179
00:09:18,089 --> 00:09:20,190
You see that?

180
00:09:20,225 --> 00:09:22,392
No, 'cause you took my glasses.

181
00:09:22,427 --> 00:09:24,227
Right there, underneath his coat.

182
00:09:24,262 --> 00:09:26,696
He's wearing a work shirt.

183
00:09:26,731 --> 00:09:28,731
"Kleg's Auto."

184
00:09:31,069 --> 00:09:33,703
Idiot. (chuckles)

185
00:09:33,738 --> 00:09:35,738
(music blaring)

186
00:09:39,211 --> 00:09:40,777
(chuckles)

187
00:09:40,812 --> 00:09:42,946
"The Red Hood Gang"! (chuckles)

188
00:09:42,981 --> 00:09:44,781
It's got a ring to it.

189
00:09:44,816 --> 00:09:46,449
- No, it doesn't.
- See those people?

190
00:09:46,485 --> 00:09:47,750
They loved me.

191
00:09:47,786 --> 00:09:49,219
They loved the money you threw at 'em.

192
00:09:49,254 --> 00:09:50,887
Thanks for that, by the way.

193
00:09:50,922 --> 00:09:52,388
Shall we take it out of your share?

194
00:09:52,424 --> 00:09:53,790
You guys don't get it.

195
00:09:53,825 --> 00:09:56,459
We're not just five mooks
with shotguns anymore.

196
00:09:56,495 --> 00:09:58,127
We're the Red Hood Gang.

197
00:09:58,163 --> 00:10:00,597
Taking from the rich and
giving back to the poor.

198
00:10:00,632 --> 00:10:02,465
Mark my words,

199
00:10:02,501 --> 00:10:04,968
the people in this town,
they're gonna get me.

200
00:10:05,937 --> 00:10:08,071
- Us.
- Will you shut up?

201
00:10:08,106 --> 00:10:09,973
All that prancing around
could have gotten us killed.

202
00:10:10,008 --> 00:10:12,242
You're wrong. That guard,
he was 20 feet away from me.

203
00:10:12,277 --> 00:10:13,610
Not one shot got close.

204
00:10:13,645 --> 00:10:14,511
Luck!

205
00:10:14,546 --> 00:10:17,013
He looked r-real nervous.

206
00:10:17,048 --> 00:10:17,914
It's the hood!

207
00:10:17,949 --> 00:10:19,616
It's good luck. I'm telling you.

208
00:10:19,651 --> 00:10:21,618
I feel like a totally
different person with it on.

209
00:10:21,653 --> 00:10:22,986
Eh, sit down, will ya?

210
00:10:23,021 --> 00:10:24,487
We need to go over tomorrow's score.

211
00:10:24,523 --> 00:10:26,656
Nah, this sets us apart.

212
00:10:26,691 --> 00:10:30,093
It's a piece of cloth...
Two holes cut out of it.

213
00:10:31,129 --> 00:10:32,729
It's a symbol!

214
00:10:32,764 --> 00:10:34,998
Whoever wears the hood

215
00:10:35,033 --> 00:10:36,366
- should lead!
- (gunshot)

216
00:10:37,035 --> 00:10:37,734
(grunts)

217
00:10:41,306 --> 00:10:43,907
(grunting)

218
00:10:49,848 --> 00:10:52,482
He's right.

219
00:10:52,517 --> 00:10:55,785
Any objections?

220
00:11:06,526 --> 00:11:07,625
So...

221
00:11:07,660 --> 00:11:11,020
you're the one causing all of the fuss.

222
00:11:12,285 --> 00:11:14,106
The one with the knife now.

223
00:11:14,141 --> 00:11:16,174
This is your facility?

224
00:11:16,210 --> 00:11:17,376
I manage it, yes.

225
00:11:17,411 --> 00:11:19,544
But do you own it?

226
00:11:19,580 --> 00:11:21,246
The doctor owns it.

227
00:11:23,666 --> 00:11:25,050
Where are you going?

228
00:11:25,085 --> 00:11:27,786
Back to the basement. We're done here.

229
00:11:27,821 --> 00:11:28,754
Miss Mooney...

230
00:11:34,928 --> 00:11:36,228
Take a seat.

231
00:11:36,263 --> 00:11:39,197
I will talk to the doctor
and the doctor only.

232
00:11:39,233 --> 00:11:41,900
He's away on a consultation in Gotham.

233
00:11:41,935 --> 00:11:43,702
Then call me when he returns.

234
00:11:43,737 --> 00:11:46,038
<i>He expressly asked me</i>

235
00:11:46,073 --> 00:11:48,206
to attend to your demands.

236
00:11:49,843 --> 00:11:51,810
His name.

237
00:11:51,845 --> 00:11:53,412
I'm sorry?

238
00:11:53,447 --> 00:11:56,248
The doctor. His name.

239
00:11:58,452 --> 00:12:00,452
Dulmacher.

240
00:12:03,257 --> 00:12:06,625
You tell Dr. Dulmacher

241
00:12:06,660 --> 00:12:09,227
that the basement is mine.

242
00:12:09,263 --> 00:12:11,430
No one will leave

243
00:12:11,465 --> 00:12:14,299
unless I say so. It will remain that way

244
00:12:14,334 --> 00:12:16,568
until he sits with me

245
00:12:16,603 --> 00:12:18,703
and negotiates terms.

246
00:12:25,813 --> 00:12:29,181
Perhaps...

247
00:12:29,216 --> 00:12:31,817
you and I got off on the
wrong foot, Miss Mooney.

248
00:12:31,852 --> 00:12:33,485
When was the last time

249
00:12:33,520 --> 00:12:36,788
you had a shower? A
new set of clothes? Hmm?

250
00:12:36,824 --> 00:12:39,157
(lock buzzes, latch clicks)

251
00:12:39,193 --> 00:12:40,258
(door opens)

252
00:12:40,294 --> 00:12:43,128
Take Miss Mooney to my private bathroom,

253
00:12:43,163 --> 00:12:46,631
and then pick up some fresh
clothes for her from storage.

254
00:12:46,667 --> 00:12:48,300
Freshen up.

255
00:12:48,335 --> 00:12:49,968
Come back to me.

256
00:12:50,003 --> 00:12:52,537
And then perhaps we'll talk some more.

257
00:12:55,809 --> 00:12:58,276
<i>COMEDIAN: So the mortician says</i>

258
00:12:58,312 --> 00:13:00,745
to the waitress... No, the
waitress says to the mortician,

259
00:13:00,781 --> 00:13:03,748
(clears throat) "He was always stiff."

260
00:13:03,784 --> 00:13:04,950
MAN 2: That's it.

261
00:13:04,985 --> 00:13:07,219
- Let's go.
- Wait. No.

262
00:13:07,254 --> 00:13:11,156
Have a good night. See
you next week, sir. Okay.

263
00:13:11,191 --> 00:13:15,026
- It's fine. We got, uh...
- Check, please.

264
00:13:15,062 --> 00:13:17,362
- (whispering)
- COMEDIAN: cards.

265
00:13:17,397 --> 00:13:18,830
Oh, okay. Um...

266
00:13:18,866 --> 00:13:20,365
