530
00:26:45,520 --> 00:26:46,586
(door closes)

531
00:26:46,621 --> 00:26:49,255
There's still business to discuss.

532
00:26:49,291 --> 00:26:50,690
Of course.

533
00:26:50,725 --> 00:26:52,191
The basement.

534
00:26:52,227 --> 00:26:54,193
How do I resume operations?

535
00:26:54,229 --> 00:26:56,863
We do have a business to run.

536
00:26:56,898 --> 00:27:00,300
Yes, you're stealing body parts.

537
00:27:00,335 --> 00:27:02,535
- For who?
- Oh!

538
00:27:02,571 --> 00:27:04,637
We have clients...

539
00:27:04,673 --> 00:27:07,941
all over the world in need of such things.

540
00:27:07,976 --> 00:27:11,878
Also, there's the doctor's

541
00:27:11,913 --> 00:27:13,913
personal experiments.

542
00:27:18,086 --> 00:27:21,872
You have such a presence,

543
00:27:21,923 --> 00:27:23,156
Miss Mooney.

544
00:27:24,993 --> 00:27:26,993
Such a gaze.

545
00:27:27,996 --> 00:27:30,763
Your eyes...

546
00:27:30,799 --> 00:27:33,199
will fetch quite a penny.

547
00:27:33,234 --> 00:27:37,770
You will take nothing from me.

548
00:27:37,806 --> 00:27:38,871
Really?

549
00:27:38,907 --> 00:27:42,275
Because the way I see it,
you have two choices: One...

550
00:27:42,310 --> 00:27:45,144
we kill you and your little
friends in the basement.

551
00:27:45,180 --> 00:27:48,815
That's an inconvenience
but an acceptable one.

552
00:27:48,850 --> 00:27:50,850
Or, two...

553
00:27:52,420 --> 00:27:54,954
we take your eyes now

554
00:27:54,990 --> 00:27:58,891
and see how long a blind girl
can survive in the basement.

555
00:28:02,864 --> 00:28:04,831
You forgot option three.

556
00:28:04,866 --> 00:28:05,732
(grunts)

557
00:28:05,767 --> 00:28:08,735
- Stop her!
- (both scream)

558
00:28:17,479 --> 00:28:19,746
- No!
- (spoon clinks)

559
00:28:20,782 --> 00:28:22,676
(thud)

560
00:28:26,271 --> 00:28:28,304
(thunder rumbles; Alfred
and Reggie converse quietly)

561
00:28:28,340 --> 00:28:30,740
I picked something out from the cellar.

562
00:28:30,776 --> 00:28:32,642
I hope that's okay.

563
00:28:33,171 --> 00:28:34,871
Well, that's, uh, extremely kind of you,

564
00:28:34,907 --> 00:28:36,907
Master Bruce, but I don't think that we...

565
00:28:38,477 --> 00:28:41,144
that I'll be, uh, drinking this evening.

566
00:28:41,179 --> 00:28:42,579
I'm sure it's perfectly fine to have

567
00:28:42,614 --> 00:28:44,547
a glass of wine occasionally, Alfred.

568
00:28:44,583 --> 00:28:46,549
I-I picked an old one.

569
00:28:46,585 --> 00:28:48,818
Seems a shame to let them
gather dust down there.

570
00:28:50,155 --> 00:28:54,190
Domaine de la Romanée-Conti.

571
00:28:57,329 --> 00:29:00,797
It's a rather nice Burgundy,
actually, it's 1966.

572
00:29:02,067 --> 00:29:03,700
Yeah.

573
00:29:03,735 --> 00:29:05,568
It's one of your father's favorites.

574
00:29:05,604 --> 00:29:07,904
(chuckles)

575
00:29:10,842 --> 00:29:13,410
Why not, eh? Take a pew.

576
00:29:15,681 --> 00:29:18,214
That's very kind of you.

577
00:29:18,250 --> 00:29:20,483
- There you go.
- Cheers, mate.

578
00:29:24,556 --> 00:29:27,090
Now, the idea, of course,

579
00:29:27,125 --> 00:29:30,727
is to let it breathe for at least an hour.

580
00:29:34,366 --> 00:29:35,765
Or not.

581
00:29:35,801 --> 00:29:37,867
- (slurps)
- (laughs)

582
00:29:37,903 --> 00:29:40,370
Ah. Delicious.

583
00:29:40,405 --> 00:29:42,172
(laughter)

584
00:29:42,207 --> 00:29:44,307
So he eventually opened his backpack

585
00:29:44,343 --> 00:29:45,709
and he found the bloody snake.

586
00:29:45,744 --> 00:29:47,777
We'd been waiting for it all night.

587
00:29:47,813 --> 00:29:49,346
He didn't even flinch.

588
00:29:49,381 --> 00:29:51,281
- What'd you do?
- Oh, you know,

589
00:29:51,316 --> 00:29:53,950
I chopped its head off and
we ate the bloody thing.

590
00:29:53,986 --> 00:29:56,252
- (laughter)
- He did.

591
00:29:56,288 --> 00:29:57,387
What did it taste like?

592
00:29:57,422 --> 00:29:59,956
ALFRED: Uh, a bit like, um, fast food.

593
00:29:59,992 --> 00:30:01,358
(all laugh)

594
00:30:01,393 --> 00:30:02,659
ALFRED: It was horrible.

595
00:30:02,694 --> 00:30:05,295
It was horrible. It was disgusting.

596
00:30:05,330 --> 00:30:06,997
BRUCE: So, um...

597
00:30:07,032 --> 00:30:08,965
so, Mr. Payne, you were in the Air Force?

598
00:30:09,001 --> 00:30:11,801
Special Air Service... SAS.

599
00:30:11,837 --> 00:30:13,370
Best soldiers in the world,

600
00:30:13,405 --> 00:30:15,538
if I'm being honest.

601
00:30:15,574 --> 00:30:17,941
So that means covert missions?

602
00:30:17,976 --> 00:30:20,076
That's right.

603
00:30:20,112 --> 00:30:21,811
Before a conflict, they dropped us

604
00:30:21,847 --> 00:30:23,780
behind enemy lines.

605
00:30:23,815 --> 00:30:27,917
We were quiet, precise, and deadly.

606
00:30:27,953 --> 00:30:29,619
We never lost a man

607
00:30:29,654 --> 00:30:31,654
and we always completed our missions.

608
00:30:34,293 --> 00:30:36,009
Except that once, I guess.

609
00:30:36,034 --> 00:30:38,995
Yeah, well, that's enough of
the old war stories, eh, Reg?

610
00:30:39,031 --> 00:30:40,997
What one time?

611
00:30:42,034 --> 00:30:44,000
REGGIE: There was a sandstorm.

612
00:30:44,036 --> 00:30:46,336
We got separated.

613
00:30:46,371 --> 00:30:48,738
Two of us were captured.

614
00:30:48,774 --> 00:30:50,840
You?

615
00:30:52,144 --> 00:30:55,612
He fought 12 of them off
before they cut him down.

616
00:30:55,647 --> 00:30:58,048
Didn't you, Alf?

617
00:30:59,818 --> 00:31:02,118
I'm here now, aren't I?

618
00:31:02,154 --> 00:31:03,486
That's all that matters.

619
00:31:03,522 --> 00:31:04,954
(sniffs)

620
00:31:04,990 --> 00:31:07,290
All right, gents, while I have to
say this has been absolutely lovely,

621
00:31:07,325 --> 00:31:09,125
I'd like to,

622
00:31:09,161 --> 00:31:11,227
I'd like to tidy up before I go to bed.

623
00:31:11,263 --> 00:31:13,430
(scoffing):
T-T-Tidy up?

624
00:31:13,465 --> 00:31:15,932
Mr. Yes Sir, No Sir.

625
00:31:15,967 --> 00:31:18,468
Mr. Queensberry rules and discipline.

626
00:31:18,503 --> 00:31:19,702
Thank you, that's enough.

627
00:31:22,908 --> 00:31:25,742
Alfred's right... it's time for bed.

628
00:31:27,345 --> 00:31:29,045
Good night, Master Bruce.

629
00:31:29,081 --> 00:31:30,713
BRUCE: Good night. Good night.

630
00:31:30,749 --> 00:31:32,749
Sleep well, son.

631
00:31:34,553 --> 00:31:36,719
Why are you hiding from
him what you really are,

632
00:31:36,755 --> 00:31:38,388
who you really are?

633
00:31:40,425 --> 00:31:43,026
You're a war dog, Alfie.

634
00:31:44,062 --> 00:31:46,029
You're a cold-blooded,

635
00:31:46,064 --> 00:31:49,332
lethal war dog, is what you are.

636
00:31:53,572 --> 00:31:56,039
I found some fresh clothes for you, Reg.

637
00:31:56,074 --> 00:31:58,141
I folded them and I put 'em on your bed,

638
00:31:58,176 --> 00:32:00,510
and I've taken the liberty of packing you

639
00:32:00,545 --> 00:32:03,813
a lunch for your travels tomorrow.

640
00:32:03,849 --> 00:32:06,382
It's been really nice to see you, Reggie.

641
00:32:07,619 --> 00:32:11,154
I see them, at night... when I'm alone.

642
00:32:12,457 --> 00:32:14,424
The faces...

643
00:32:14,459 --> 00:32:17,260
the faces of those we killed.

644
00:32:17,295 --> 00:32:18,695
Do you?

645
00:32:18,730 --> 00:32:22,031
I don't have to look for them, Reg.

646
00:32:24,069 --> 00:32:26,503
They find me.

647
00:32:57,369 --> 00:32:59,002
(startled shout)

648
00:32:59,037 --> 00:33:01,271
(gasps, chuckles)

649
00:33:01,306 --> 00:33:03,173
Holy crap.

650
00:33:03,208 --> 00:33:04,908
You scared the snot out of me.

651
00:33:04,943 --> 00:33:07,310
H-Had to see you.
I c-couldn't wait.

652
00:33:07,345 --> 00:33:09,846
- Where were you?
- Out.

653
00:33:09,881 --> 00:33:12,115
J-Just out?

654
00:33:12,150 --> 00:33:14,350
What's it to you?

655
00:33:14,386 --> 00:33:16,586
I need the hood.

656
00:33:16,621 --> 00:33:17,587
What?

657
00:33:17,622 --> 00:33:19,455
- No.
- M...

658
00:33:19,491 --> 00:33:21,457
My-my girlfriend, sh-she
wants... she wants to leave.

659
00:33:21,493 --> 00:33:24,494
She... she called me a loser last night.

660
00:33:24,529 --> 00:33:26,896
Her ex is back in town. He's a b-bouncer.

661
00:33:26,932 --> 00:33:28,498
I figured she-she sees me

662
00:33:28,533 --> 00:33:31,834
in the hood, she's got... she's
got to take me s-seriously.

663
00:33:31,870 --> 00:33:34,470
Did you ransack my place looking for it?

664
00:33:34,506 --> 00:33:35,772
I need it, Destro.

665
00:33:35,807 --> 00:33:38,308
They're talking about it on the streets

666
00:33:38,343 --> 00:33:40,398
and in the news. She
sees me in it, and I'm...

667
00:33:40,423 --> 00:33:41,851
No!

668
00:33:41,926 --> 00:33:44,681
We have one last job before
we split up and skip town.

669
00:33:50,088 --> 00:33:51,955
(gun cocks)

670
00:33:51,990 --> 00:33:53,690
You have it on you, don't you?

671
00:33:53,725 --> 00:33:56,759
You better use that thing

672
00:33:56,795 --> 00:33:58,861
before I make you eat it.

673
00:34:00,899 --> 00:34:02,165
(gunshot)

674
00:34:06,671 --> 00:34:08,671
(door creaking)

675
00:34:10,842 --> 00:34:14,043
- (gasping weakly)
- He's alive.

676
00:34:15,213 --> 00:34:16,646
(stairs rattling)

677
00:34:16,681 --> 00:34:18,047
Who shot you, Destro? Give us the name

678
00:34:18,083 --> 00:34:20,049
- of the guy.
- I need an ambulance.

679
00:34:20,085 --> 00:34:22,352
We'll get to that. Give us the
names of the guys in your crew.

680
00:34:22,387 --> 00:34:24,220
I'm bleeding out.

681
00:34:24,256 --> 00:34:25,521
Yeah, you're dying.

682
00:34:25,557 --> 00:34:27,490
And, unfortunately, I'm
not getting cell reception.

683
00:34:27,525 --> 00:34:28,691
You know what might help?

684
00:34:28,727 --> 00:34:30,827
Giving us the names of
the guys in your crew!

685
00:34:30,862 --> 00:34:32,161
GORDON: I need an ambulance.

686
00:34:32,197 --> 00:34:34,030
Java Heights and Homewood, apartment 466.

687
00:34:34,065 --> 00:34:37,233
I might need some pressure on this wound.

688
00:34:37,269 --> 00:34:39,736
- Knock yourself out.
- (panting)

689
00:34:40,772 --> 00:34:43,740
What do you got there, partner?

690
00:34:43,775 --> 00:34:45,808
A stack of loan rejection
letters from the banks

691
00:34:45,844 --> 00:34:47,277
that were robbed.

692
00:34:47,312 --> 00:34:49,946
"Dear Mr. Destro, we regret
to inform you your application

693
00:34:49,981 --> 00:34:51,547
for a loan has been denied."

694
00:34:51,583 --> 00:34:54,217
"Mr. Destro, once again, we
must deny your application,

695
00:34:54,252 --> 00:34:55,785
due to inadequate collateral."

696
00:34:55,820 --> 00:34:57,620
What the hell would he need a loan for?

697
00:34:57,656 --> 00:34:59,289
Pastry shop.

698
00:34:59,324 --> 00:35:01,557
Get out of here. You're a baker?

699
00:35:01,593 --> 00:35:03,426
A damn good baker.

700
00:35:03,461 --> 00:35:04,761
And they all turned you down.

701
00:35:04,796 --> 00:35:06,896
So these are revenge robberies.

702
00:35:06,931 --> 00:35:08,865
Banks don't care about people like me.

703
00:35:08,900 --> 00:35:11,067
Or you, probably.

704
00:35:11,102 --> 00:35:13,536
You have to force people to see you.

705
00:35:13,571 --> 00:35:15,605
Otherwise, you're nothing.

706
00:35:15,640 --> 00:35:18,074
There's a third letter here.
International Savings Bank

707
00:35:18,109 --> 00:35:20,543
of Gotham... this was the next target.

708
00:35:20,578 --> 00:35:22,545
Where's my ambulance?

709
00:35:35,794 --> 00:35:38,828
To new beginnings.

710
00:35:38,863 --> 00:35:40,430
(sniffs)

711
00:35:40,465 --> 00:35:42,231
I'm not trying to poison you, son.

712
00:35:42,267 --> 00:35:44,067
Forgive me if I'm a little cautious.

713
00:35:44,102 --> 00:35:45,935
If this club tanks,

714
00:35:45,970 --> 00:35:48,771
Falcone's not gonna
trust either of us again.

715
00:35:48,807 --> 00:35:50,940
I don't know about you,

716
00:35:50,975 --> 00:35:53,943
but I'm done playing the sidekick.

717
00:35:54,979 --> 00:35:58,981
To no longer being a sidekick.

718
00:36:14,666 --> 00:36:17,100
Do you miss her?

719
00:36:18,536 --> 00:36:20,169
I do.

720
00:36:20,205 --> 00:36:21,571
(chuckles)

721
00:36:21,606 --> 00:36:23,039
Even after everything she did to me.

722
00:36:24,909 --> 00:36:27,343
Perhaps it's not our friends but...

723
00:36:27,379 --> 00:36:29,545
our enemies that define us.

724
00:36:31,983 --> 00:36:34,016
To Fish.

725
00:36:36,454 --> 00:36:39,455
She got what she deserved.

726
00:36:46,097 --> 00:36:48,097
(thunder rumbling)

727
00:36:49,100 --> 00:36:51,100
(rattling, clattering)

728
00:36:59,577 --> 00:37:01,577
(rattling, clattering continue)

729
00:37:06,718 --> 00:37:10,686
You're stealing from us?

730
00:37:10,722 --> 00:37:13,990
You could have just
asked me for money, Reg.

731
00:37:14,025 --> 00:37:18,327
You don't know how hard
that is, Alfie... do you?

732
00:37:18,363 --> 00:37:20,663
We gave you somewhere to sleep.

733
00:37:20,698 --> 00:37:23,499
We put food in your belly.

734
00:37:23,535 --> 00:37:25,868
I'm in trouble.

735
00:37:25,904 --> 00:37:27,603
Real trouble.

736
00:37:27,639 --> 00:37:29,672
I don't need a lecture right now.

737
00:37:34,646 --> 00:37:37,079
What kind of trouble?

738
00:37:37,115 --> 00:37:39,015
You don't want to know.

739
00:37:39,050 --> 00:37:41,484
Right. Well, you put the bag down

740
00:37:41,519 --> 00:37:43,486
and you leave.

741
00:37:43,521 --> 00:37:46,289
Now.

742
00:37:46,324 --> 00:37:50,526
Did you bring a gun, Alfie?

743
00:37:50,562 --> 00:37:52,929
No.

744
00:37:52,964 --> 00:37:56,265
If there was any other way...

745
00:37:56,301 --> 00:37:59,302
Oh, come on... there's
always another way, mate.

746
00:38:01,439 --> 00:38:03,039
I'm sorry.

747
00:38:03,074 --> 00:38:04,240
Sorry f...

748
00:38:04,275 --> 00:38:06,742
(grunting)

749
00:38:07,779 --> 00:38:10,313
I'm so sorry.

750
00:38:12,750 --> 00:38:14,750
(coughs)

751
00:38:29,901 --> 00:38:31,567
(no voice)

752
00:38:31,603 --> 00:38:34,170
(dialing phone)

753
00:38:34,205 --> 00:38:35,371
Th-This is Bruce Wayne.

754
00:38:35,406 --> 00:38:37,340
I need immediate help at Wayne Manor!

755
00:38:37,375 --> 00:38:38,641
My friend has been stabbed.

756
00:38:40,879 --> 00:38:45,281
Alfred... Alfred, Alfred, look
at me... you're gonna be okay.

757
00:38:45,316 --> 00:38:47,283
Alfred, stay with me.

758
00:38:47,318 --> 00:38:49,652
(voice breaking): Please.

759
00:38:53,248 --> 00:38:54,526
Alfred!

760
00:39:01,156 --> 00:39:02,955
(tires screech)

761
00:39:06,523 --> 00:39:09,055
There's only three of us.

762
00:39:09,056 --> 00:39:11,189
I'm worried. If someone
makes a move in there...

763
00:39:11,227 --> 00:39:13,226
Don't be.

764
00:39:16,261 --> 00:39:18,260
I have this.

765
00:39:24,761 --> 00:39:27,993
(tires screeching)

766
00:39:29,027 --> 00:39:31,860
GORDON (over bullhorn): GCPD!

767
00:39:31,861 --> 00:39:33,826
We have you surrounded!

768
00:39:33,827 --> 00:39:37,860
This doesn't have to end
badly! Put down your guns!

769
00:39:37,861 --> 00:39:39,260
Suck it, coppers!

770
00:39:39,261 --> 00:39:42,093
(gunfire)

771
00:39:42,094 --> 00:39:44,226
(laughing)

772
00:39:49,427 --> 00:39:51,360
OFFICER (echoing): Man down! Man down!

773
00:39:57,394 --> 00:39:59,726
(clicking) GORDON: Hold your fire!

774
00:39:59,727 --> 00:40:00,727
OFFICER: Hold your fire!

775
00:40:00,728 --> 00:40:02,726
Drop it!

776
00:40:04,894 --> 00:40:07,093
It's over.

777
00:40:07,094 --> 00:40:09,760
Yeah?

778
00:40:09,761 --> 00:40:12,260
Don't be so sure.

779
00:40:12,261 --> 00:40:14,093
(gunfire)

780
00:40:33,327 --> 00:40:34,826
(sniffs)

781
00:40:42,761 --> 00:40:45,493
I need a Danish.

782
00:40:48,061 --> 00:40:50,593
(phone ringing)

783
00:40:51,827 --> 00:40:53,626
Yeah.

784
00:40:56,361 --> 00:40:59,226
Which hospital?

785
00:41:03,261 --> 00:41:05,260
(monitor beeping steadily)

786
00:41:18,094 --> 00:41:20,760
(voice breaking): I can't lose him.

787
00:41:21,762 --> 00:41:24,760
He's all I have.

788
00:41:29,761 --> 00:41:31,626
(crying)

789
00:41:44,861 --> 00:41:47,326
REGGIE: He has nothing concrete.

790
00:41:47,327 --> 00:41:51,793
Just faces, some dates,

791
00:41:51,794 --> 00:41:53,793
some newspaper articles.

792
00:41:53,794 --> 00:41:56,726
There's no grounds for an investigation.

793
00:41:56,727 --> 00:41:59,193
Just... suspicions...

794
00:41:59,194 --> 00:42:02,360
some cobbled-together theories...

795
00:42:02,361 --> 00:42:05,026
Nothing.

796
00:42:05,027 --> 00:42:07,193
WOMAN: Has he had outside counsel?

797
00:42:07,194 --> 00:42:09,326
I don't think so.

798
00:42:09,327 --> 00:42:12,726
WOMAN: And his caretaker, Mr. Pennyworth?

799
00:42:12,727 --> 00:42:15,193
He's in the hospital.

800
00:42:15,194 --> 00:42:17,793
